{
  "doc_id": "34631",
  "text": "Over the past two decades, umbilical cord blood (UCB) has developed into an attractive and alternative source of hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) both in clinics and in research. However, insufficient numbers of HSCs in the UCB limits its application in adults as an allogeneic source of HSCs for the transplantation [CITATION_1] . The limited cell dose can be enhanced either by performing double CB transplantation (DCBT) or by ex vivo expansion of UCB. Ex vivo expansion stands out to be the most convenient option over the DCBT since, in the latter, there is successful engraftment of only a single CB unit with an elevated risk of graft versus host disease [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
